=== INTRO_100 ===
# id: INTRO_100
# mode: day
# history_root
~ set_header("Diner, Bank Street, Ottawa", "Monday morning")
// Scene state object — persists across passages (unlike $temp which resets)
// reset scene state ($briefing = {})
~ briefing_read_robert = false
~ briefing_called_out = false
The diner smells like coffee that's been on the burner since six and bacon grease that's been in the ventilation since before the [url=gloss:Diefenbunker]Diefenbunker[/url] was built.  A place on [url=gloss:Bank Street]Bank Street[/url] south of Gloucester, no sign worth reading, where the booths are brown vinyl and the light is the colour of weak tea.  Half the clientele are civil servants eating before the buildings open, career government workers worried that the minority Liberal parliament might lose a confidence vote.  Nobody looks at you twice, which is the point.
You're early.  You're always early for Robert.  Mostly because it pisses him off.  He loves you for it though.
* [Sip your coffee.] -> INTRO_101

// Waiting
=== INTRO_105 ===
# id: INTRO_105
# mode: day
~ set_header("Diner, Bank Street, Ottawa", "Monday morning")
The waitress brings coffee without being asked — you've been here before, enough times that she recognizes the booth but not your name.  Her name is Gladys.  You wrap your hands around the mug and watch the door.
Outside, an [url=gloss:OC Transpo]OC Transpo[/url] bus grinds past on [url=gloss:Bank Street]Bank[/url], throwing diesel haze across the sidewalk.  September in Ottawa.  Still warm, but the light has changed — that particular quality of autumn sun that makes the limestone go yellow.
{
- background == "RCMP constable":
    You used to drink coffee like this at the detachment — institutional, slightly burnt.  The ritual is the same even if the context has shifted.
- background == "CSIS analyst":
    You used to meet sources in places like this.  The tradecraft is the same.
- background == "grad student":
    There's a woman two booths over eating eggs alone and staring at nothing.  The part of your brain that studied behavioural patterns can't stop reading the room.  You look away.  Not a case study.
- else:
    Two years ago you wouldn't have known what to look for in a diner — the exits, the sightlines, the two men at the counter reading the same section of the Citizen.
}
* [Continue] -> INTRO_110

// Robert arrives
=== INTRO_110 ===
# id: INTRO_110
# mode: day
~ set_header("Diner, Bank Street, Ottawa", "Monday morning")
// [image] media/characters/robert-flett-diner-entry.png — native presentation TBD
Robert Flett arrives at 8:14, which means he was in the neighbourhood by 7:45 and spent the intervening time making sure he wasn't followed.  You know this because he taught you to do the same thing, and because he's carrying a copy of the [url=gloss:Globe]Globe[/url] that looks like it's already been read.  It's a ridiculous thing to do half a block from the office, but it's [i]because[/i] you're a known regular here — Robert dropping in once doesn't read as a meet.  You smile that he does the newspaper bit anyway.
He doesn't look like a man who tracks the inexplicable for a living.  He looks like a mid-level bureaucrat — brown skin you've long since placed as [url=gloss:Métis]Métis[/url], hair going grey at the temples, a jacket that's seen better years.  He grew up in [url=gloss:Shield country]Shield country[/url] between the [url=gloss:Sault]Sault[/url] and [url=gloss:Thunder Bay]Thunder Bay[/url].
* [The one thing that doesn't match is his hands.] -> INTRO_115

// Morning
=== INTRO_115 ===
# id: INTRO_115
# mode: day
~ set_header("Diner, Bank Street, Ottawa", "Monday morning")
Working hands, scarred across the knuckles.  You noticed them the first day you met him, two years ago, and you still don't know the story.  Especially since you do know the story of how he was an academic at [url=gloss:Lakehead]Lakehead[/url] and a star grad student at [url=gloss:U of T]U of T[/url].  But who knows what he's seen in the dark of the woods.
He slides into the booth across from you, sets the [url=gloss:Globe]Globe[/url] on the table, and catches the waitress's eye.  Coffee.  No food yet.
"Morning," he says.
